85 to 75 Christopher Street, north side, west of and towards upper West 4th Street and Seventh Avenue South. No. 81 is St. John's Evangelical Lutheran (German) Church, which was established here around the time of the Civil War; but the church edifice itself was probably inherited from St. Mathew's Protestant Episcopal Church, which stood on the same site.

Seventh Avenue South, east side, and 76-70 Grove Street, at and south of the Sheridan Square subway station at West 4th Street. The subway entrance is in a little island which used to be the N.W. corner of Grove (formerly Burrows Street, originally Columbia Street) and West 4th (formerly Asylum Street) Streets. Sheridan Square (q.v.) is properly the triangular open space shown here in the left background, but it is loosely applied to both sides of Seventh Avenue South, from Christopher to Grove Streets, inclusive.
About 1928.

Ewing Galloway.

Seventh Avenue South, west side, north from 4th Street. Winter, 1933.

P. L. Sperr.

4th Street (to the left) north from Christopher Street, at Seventh Avenue South. This part of 4th Street is an old Village street, shown on an 1803 map as Chester Street and on the 1811 city survey (when the numbered streets and avenues were first planned) as William Street. Before long, however, the true 4th Street on the East Side was extended to this point, and that number was applied to this street all the way to its terminus at 13th and
Gansevoort Streets, west of Eighth Avenue.
The block on the east side of 4th Street, from Christopher to 10th (formerly Amos) Streets, was broken up when Seventh Avenue South was cut through around 1914. All that was left west of Seventh Avenue South were Nos. 229-31 West 4th Street, shown in this picture with the Sinclair Motor 0il advertisement on the side of 229. The building shown in part on the left is the new one built in 1931 on the site of the Greenwich Village Theatre, which itself was built on the old N.W. corner of 4th and Christopher Streets after Seventh
Avenue South was cut through.
233 West 4th Street, on the N.E. corner of 10th Street, is a fairly
new apartment house.
March 25, 1933.
P. L. Sperr.

4th Street (right), and Washington Place (left), east from Grove Street, showing also Sheridan Square in the foreground. Sheridan Square is a triangle with its apex pointing west and located at the western end of Washington Place (originally West 5th Street); the northern side is the northern side of Washington Place, and the southern side follows the line of West 4th Street (formerly Asylum Street). Sheridan Square house numbers begin on the short eastern side, which was originally the eastern end of Reason Street (now the eastern section of Barrow Street, q.v.), and follow in order clockwise around Sheridan Square.

P. L. Sperr.

June 24, 1933.
